# AI system

## Entry point
- `makeAIMove()` in `src/ai.ts` is the primary AI used by `App.tsx`.
- It calls `makeAIPlacement()` then `makeAIPieceSelection()` separately for place and give phases.

## Heuristic AI (`src/ai.ts`)
Difficulty levels: `easy` | `normal` | `hard` | `brutal`.

| Level | Random move chance | Win-check skip chance | Min safe pieces |
|-------|-------------------|----------------------|-----------------|
| easy | 40% | 50% | 2 |
| normal | 20% | 20% | 2 |
| hard | 10% | 5% | 3 |
| brutal | 0% | 0% | 8 |

Constants are at the top of `ai.ts`. Logic priorities:
1. Take immediate wins when not skipped by difficulty.
2. Block opponent wins.
3. Prefer placements/pieces that leave enough safe options (min safe pieces threshold).
4. Fall back to random moves per difficulty.

Enable `enableLogging` on `AIInput` for console decision traces.

## MCTS module (`src/ai/mcts.ts`, `src/ai/mctsPlayer.ts`)
- Separate Monte Carlo Tree Search implementation with configurable iterations and playout depth.
- `MCTSAIPlayer.getBestMove()` wraps the search engine.
- Not wired as the default in `makeAIMove()` — extend or swap callers in `App.tsx` to use MCTS.
- Preserve separation: keep MCTS state/search in `ai/mcts.ts`, keep app-facing API thin in `mctsPlayer.ts`.

## When changing AI
- Tune constants in `ai.ts` rather than hard-coding magic numbers in functions.
- Test all four difficulty levels and both phases (place and give).
- Winning placement ends the turn early — no piece is given after a win.
